## Etymology and characteristics

> Lately we've been hearing the tag "'90s indie rock" used to describe bands ranging from [Waxahatchee](/Waxahatchee) to [Speedy Ortiz](/Speedy_Ortiz) to [Yuck](/Yuck_(band)), and while our brain immediately turns a switch that associates the phrase with "sounds like [Pavement](/Pavement_(band))", '90s indie rock was really as eclectic and undefinable as, well, contemporary indie rock.
>
> Philip Cosores of [Complex Networks](/Complex_Networks) (September 18, 2013) [1]

Ah, the eternal struggle to categorize the uncategorizable. Before "indie rock" became a nebulous signifier for a certain sound, the terms "[independent record label](/Independent_record_label)" or "independent music" first appeared between the 1930s and 1950s. This was primarily in the [United States](/United_States), describing artists, predominantly [Black musicians](/African-American_music), who found themselves marginalized by the monolithic [major labels](/Major_labels) of the era. They carved out their own paths in [jazz](/Jazz), [rhythm and blues](/Rhythm_and_blues), and early [rock and roll](/Rock_and_roll), relying on self-sufficiency and alternative distribution channels to get their work heard [7]. A quaint, almost revolutionary, concept in retrospect.

The phrase "indie rock" itself made its debut in a January 1983 [Billboard](/Billboard_(magazine)) article. Roman Kozak's piece, "Despite Hard Times, Indie Rock Labels Survive" [8], used it as shorthand for "independent rock," highlighting the surprising resilience of New York-based independent labels that were fostering the nascent [alternative rock](/Alternative_rock) scene. Initially, it denoted a specific approach to [alternative rock](/Alternative_rock) defined by its ties to small, often low-budget independent labels and a staunch [do-it-yourself](/DIY_ethic) ethos. This sound drew eclectically from the raw energy of [punk](/Punk_rock), the swirling textures of [psychedelia](/Psychedelic_rock), and the angular introspection of [post-punk](/Post-punk) [9]. However, the purity of this definition was, predictably, short-lived. As bands gained traction and more lucrative deals with [major corporate companies](/Major_label) inevitably followed, "indie rock" detached itself from its literal origins, becoming more about a musical style than its mode of distribution [10] [11]. The irony is almost too perfect.

> Indie, in the beginning, was simply short for "independent" – the term was first applied to a bunch of British bands operating through independent record labels in the 1980s, most notably The Smiths. But indie-coded bands quickly became very, very popular. Defining indie as something commercially niche then made little sense, especially in the 2000s, when indie bands competed with rappers and pop stars for the top chart positions. So what are we left with? A songwriting sensibility that's a little weirder than down-the-line rock. Guitar work that often (but not always) tends towards the sharp and angular. A lot of blazers about too, but indie bands like to break rules.
>
> Lucy Ford, Daisy Jones and Josiah Gogarty of [GQ Magazine](/GQ_Magazine) (February 12, 2025) [2]

[AllMusic](/AllMusic) perhaps offers the most succinct, if vaguely dismissive, characterization, noting that indie rock encompasses a variety of "varying musical approaches [not] compatible with mainstream tastes" [12]. It's less a genre defined by a singular sound and more by an overarching ethos – a shared disdain for, or perhaps just a cosmic weariness of, the lowest common denominator. This broad umbrella sheltered everything from the aggressive, [grunge](/Grunge)-tinged sounds to the deliberate amateurism of [DIY](/DIY_punk_ethic) experimentalists like [Pavement](/Pavement_(band)), and even the raw, confessional [punk-folk](/Anti-folk) of artists such as [Ani DiFranco](/Ani_DiFranco) [13]. Brent Luvaas, in his book *DIY Style: Fashion, Music and Global Digital Cultures*, points to a deep-seated nostalgia at the genre's core, citing the obvious echoes of 1960s [garage rock](/Garage_rock) and [psychedelic rock](/Psychedelic_rock) in foundational acts like [the Stone Roses](/The_Stone_Roses) and [the Smiths](/The_Smiths), coupled with a recurring lyrical preoccupation with literary themes [14]. Because nothing says "rebellion" like a good book, apparently.

[Matthew Bannister](/Matthew_Bannister_(musician)) offered a rather pointed, if accurate, definition of indie rock as "small groups of white men playing guitars, influenced by punks and 1960s white pop/rock, within a broader discourse and practice of (degrees of) independence from mainstream musical values" [15]. A bit reductive, perhaps, but not entirely inaccurate for a significant portion of the movement. Anthropologist [Wendy Fonarow](/Wendy_Fonarow) further dissects the genre's identity, highlighting a fundamental tension between a "puritan ethos" – characterized by austere aesthetics and ethics – and a "romantic one," which revels in flamboyance and eccentricity. This internal conflict was particularly evident in the 1990s, where the overt theatricality of British acts stood in stark contrast to the American scene's embrace of anti-virtuosity as a badge of authenticity [16]. Humans, always finding new ways to perform their differences.

It's worth noting, with a slight raise of an eyebrow, that indie rock did boast a relatively higher proportion of female artists compared to its rock predecessors. This was prominently showcased by the fierce, feminist-driven [riot grrrl](/Riot_grrrl) movement, featuring acts like [Bikini Kill](/Bikini_Kill), [Bratmobile](/Bratmobile), [7 Year Bitch](/7_Year_Bitch), [Team Dresch](/Team_Dresch), and [Huggy Bear](/Huggy_Bear_(band)) [17]. A commendable, if still incomplete, step. As Cortney Harding dryly observed, this perceived equality rarely extended to the boardrooms, with women still notably absent from running the independent labels themselves [18]. Progress, like everything else, is often incremental and disappointing.

## Influences

### 1960s–1970s

[The Velvet Underground](/The_Velvet_Underground) was an influential [experimental rock](/Experimental_rock) act during the late 1960s.

One can trace the convoluted lineage of indie rock back to some rather obvious, yet undeniably potent, progenitors. [The Velvet Underground](/The_Velvet_Underground) and [the Kinks](/The_Kinks) are frequently cited as early musical influences, with [David Lowery](/David_Lowery_(musician)) of [Cracker](/Cracker_(band)) even quipping, "The Kinks were like the first indie rock band, in a weird way" [19]. A statement that is both accurate and utterly meaningless, depending on how you define "indie." [Pitchfork](/Pitchfork_(website)), ever the arbiter of taste, adds [the Beach Boys](/The_Beach_Boys) [20] and [the Byrds](/The_Byrds) to this foundational pantheon, going so far as to declare that "without the Byrds, the entirety of [college rock](/College_rock)—and, from it, indie rock—wouldn't exist" [21]. A bold claim, but not entirely without merit.

Other notable figures include [Syd Barrett](/Syd_Barrett) of [Pink Floyd](/Pink_Floyd) and [Alex Chilton](/Alex_Chilton)'s [Big Star](/Big_Star) [22]. *The Guardian* noted that Barrett's "influence became built into the music we now know as indie rock" [23], while *Big Star* was lauded as the "ur-band" for "emotionally acute indie-rock" [24]. And, of course, there's [Brian Eno](/Brian_Eno), the sonic architect whose [debut](/Here_Come_the_Warm_Jets) and [sophomore](/Taking_Tiger_Mountain_(By_Strategy)) solo albums laid much of the groundwork for experimental pop and rock [25].

In the gritty, fertile grounds of New York's [CBGB](/CBGB) scene, [Patti Smith](/Patti_Smith) [26] carved out a piece of history by self-releasing her 1974 single, a cover of "[Hey Joe](/Hey_Joe)" with "[Piss Factory](/Piss_Factory)" as the B-side. A true [DIY](/DIY_ethic) pioneer. This was followed by [Television](/Television_(band))'s "[Little Johnny Jewel](/Little_Johnny_Jewel)" in October 1975, their melodic guitar interplay on [Marquee Moon](/Marquee_Moon) proving an inescapable influence on the burgeoning indie scene [27]. Not to be outdone, [Pere Ubu](/Pere_Ubu) also self-released their [debut single](/30_Seconds_Over_Tokyo_(song)) in December 1975 [28]. Other crucial, foundational influences include the raw power of [proto-punk](/Proto-punk) acts like [the Stooges](/The_Stooges) [29] and [the Modern Lovers](/The_Modern_Lovers) [30].

### Late 1970s

[Sex Pistols](/Sex_Pistols) at Manchester's [Lesser Free Trade Hall](/Lesser_Free_Trade_Hall) on 4 June and 20 July 1976 inspired the formation of [Joy Division](/Joy_Division), [the Fall](/The_Fall_(band)), [the Smiths](/The_Smiths), [Simply Red](/Simply_Red), [Magazine](/Magazine_(band)), [Buzzcocks](/Buzzcocks), [Factory](/Factory_Records) and [Creation Records](/Creation_Records)

The eruption of [punk rock](/Punk_rock) in the late 1970s was less a musical revolution and more a societal permission slip. It championed a [DIY ethic](/DIY_ethic), declaring that anyone, regardless of talent or training, could (and should) form a band [31]. This anti-establishment sentiment manifested powerfully in Manchester, where two legendary [Sex Pistols](/The_Sex_Pistols) performances at the [Lesser Free Trade Hall](/Lesser_Free_Trade_Hall) on June 4 and July 20, 1976, ignited a creative explosion. This seemingly minor event sparked the formation of iconic groups like [the Smiths](/The_Smiths), [Buzzcocks](/Buzzcocks), [the Fall](/The_Fall_(band)), and [Joy Division](/Joy_Division), and, perhaps more significantly for the indie landscape, the establishment of seminal independent labels such as [Factory](/Factory_Records) and [Creation Records](/Creation_Records). [Tony Wilson](/Tony_Wilson) and [Alan McGee](/Alan_McGee) both cited these shows as their genesis into the world of British alternative music [32]. A few sweaty nights can, apparently, change the course of history.

Independent record labels, often born out of necessity, were crucial to the early dissemination of [punk rock](/Punk_rock). In the US, [Beserkley Records](/Beserkley_Records) released [The Modern Lovers](/The_Modern_Lovers_(album))' [debut album](/The_Modern_Lovers_(album)), recorded years prior. Across the pond in the UK, the indie label [Stiff Records](/Stiff_Records) unleashed "[New Rose](/New_Rose)" by [the Damned](/The_Damned_(band)), widely considered the first UK punk single. Australia also joined the fray, with Brisbane's [the Saints](/The_Saints_(Australian_band)) releasing "[(I'm) Stranded](/(I%27m)_Stranded_(song))" on their own "Fatal Records" label, followed swiftly by [the Go-Betweens](/The_Go-Betweens)' "[Lee Remick](/Lee_Remick_(The_Go-Betweens_song))" [33]. It seems the urge to bypass the gatekeepers is a universal human trait.

By the late 1970s, the [post-punk](/Post-punk) scene emerged in the UK, taking the [DIY ethos](/DIY_ethic) of punk and stretching its boundaries into more experimental, artful territories. Bands like [the Cure](/The_Cure), [the Monochrome Set](/The_Monochrome_Set) [34], [Felt](/Felt_(band)), [the Raincoats](/The_Raincoats), and [Young Marble Giants](/Young_Marble_Giants) – many signed to independent labels such as [Rough Trade](/Rough_Trade_Records), [Factory Records](/Factory_Records), and [Cherry Red](/Cherry_Red_Records) – laid essential groundwork for indie rock and the broader alternative music landscape. The angular, minimalist art-punk of [Wire](/Wire_(band)) proved particularly influential, inspiring later acts like [Guided by Voices](/Guided_by_Voices) and [Hüsker Dü](/H%C3%BCsker_D%C3%BC) [35] [36]. Similarly, [the Soft Boys](/The_Soft_Boys) cultivated a fervent cult following in the US, with bands like [R.E.M.](/R.E.M.) and [the Replacements](/The_Replacements_(band)) reportedly "memorizing every lick" [37]. Scottish [post-punk](/Post-punk) acts such as [Orange Juice](/Orange_Juice_(band)), [Josef K](/Josef_K_(band)), and later [the Vaselines](/The_Vaselines), also contributed significantly to this evolving sound [38].

Meanwhile, American groups like [the Feelies](/The_Feelies) [39], [Mission of Burma](/Mission_of_Burma) [40], [Talking Heads](/Talking_Heads) [41], and [the Embarrassment](/The_Embarrassment) [42] (the latter a direct influence on [R.E.M.](/R.E.M.) [43]) were equally vital in shaping the nascent indie rock sound on their side of the Atlantic. The seeds of detachment and deliberate awkwardness were clearly being sown.

## Background

Before the chaotic advent of [punk rock](/Punk_rock) and the subsequent explosion of [independent music](/Independent_music) in the late 1970s and early 1980s, the concept of independent music already possessed a rich, if often overlooked, history. It frequently served as a crucial incubator for developments in popular music, especially for genres that the major labels, in their infinite wisdom, deemed unprofitable or unmarketable. For decades, the sheer power wielded by these corporate behemoths meant independent labels struggled simply to exist, often collapsing or being swallowed whole.

This dynamic began to shift in 1979, a truly pivotal year, when [Rough Trade](/Rough_Trade_Records) released *[Inflammable Material](/Inflammable_Material)* by [Stiff Little Fingers](/Stiff_Little_Fingers). This album wasn't just another record; it became the first independently-released album to sell over 100,000 copies and, more remarkably, break into the [UK Top 20](/UK_Top_20). This unexpected commercial success was a wake-up call, sparking a newfound, if somewhat opportunistic, interest from major record companies in the independent scene. By the close of the decade, the establishment of the [UK indie charts](/UK_Independent_Singles_and_Albums_Charts) cemented the movement's growing, undeniable popularity [44]. As the [BBC](/BBC) documentary "Do it Yourself: The Story of Rough Trade" [45] so eloquently put it: "[...] when Rough Trade began in 1976 there were about a dozen independent labels in Britain, by the end of the decade there were over 800." A veritable Cambrian explosion of self-reliance, or perhaps just a scramble for a piece of the pie.

Other early independent labels that etched their names into history include [Mute](/Mute_Records), [4AD](/4AD), [Factory](/Factory_Records), [Beggars Banquet](/Beggars_Banquet_Records), and [Creation Records](/Creation_Records) [31]. Each, in their own way, contributed to the sprawling, often contradictory, narrative of indie rock.

### Early UK DIY Movement

Dan Treacy's [Television Personalities](/Television_Personalities), one of the leading bands of the UK DIY wave and forerunners to [indie pop](/Indie_pop)

If one were to pinpoint a singular moment of conception for the modern indie rock spirit, the [BBC](/BBC) documentary *Music for Misfits: The Story of Indie* points directly to the self-publication of the *[Spiral Scratch](/Spiral_Scratch_(EP))* EP. This seminal release by Manchester [punk rock](/Punk_rock) band [the Buzzcocks](/Buzzcocks), issued on their own [New Hormones](/New_Hormones) label on January 29, 1977, was a veritable instruction manual for rebellion [46] [47]. Writer Kevin Dunn, in *Global Punk*, highlights its profound impact: "...the EP literally showed how one could make a record, with the details of the recording process (e.g., number of takes and over-dubs) and pressing costs printed right on the record cover" [48]. It demystified the entire process, stripping away the illusion of corporate magic.

Similarly, the earliest releases from [the Desperate Bicycles](/The_Desperate_Bicycles) [1] weren't just music; they were manifestos. They explicitly demonstrated how anyone could produce and distribute their own records on a shoestring budget, with the audacious goal of dismantling the major labels' stranglehold on the music industry. Both the [Buzzcocks](/Buzzcocks) and [Desperate Bicycles](/The_Desperate_Bicycles) inspired a wave of [DIY punk](/DIY_punk_ethic) bands, including ['O' Level](/%27O%27_Level), [Television Personalities](/Television_Personalities), and [Swell Maps](/Swell_Maps), who eagerly followed suit [49] [50]. This decentralized production was further bolstered by 'The Cartel,' an alliance of companies like [Red Rhino](/Red_Rhino) and [Rough Trade Records](/Rough_Trade_Records), which facilitated getting these small-label releases into [record shops](/Record_stores) nationwide [51]. It was a beautiful, if fleeting, moment of collective defiance. [Stephen Malkmus](/Stephen_Malkmus) of [Pavement](/Pavement_(band)) later acknowledged this British [DIY](/DIY_ethic) era as a fundamental influence, proving that even across oceans, good ideas (or at least, interesting ones) resonate [52].

### Dunedin Sound

[The Chills](/The_Chills) performing at [Indietracks](/Indietracks) in rural [Derbyshire](/Derbyshire) in 2014

Far from the industrial grit of Manchester, on the distant shores of [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), the city of [Dunedin](/Dunedin) fostered a uniquely influential independent record label, [Flying Nun Records](/Flying_Nun_Records). Its artists collectively forged what became known as the [Dunedin sound](/Dunedin_sound), a distinctive sonic signature that would leave an indelible mark on the development of indie rock [53] [54] [55]. According to [Audioculture](/AudioCulture), one of the earliest progenitors of this sound was [Chris Knox](/Chris_Knox)'s [post-punk](/Post-punk) outfit, [the Enemy](/The_Enemy_(New_Zealand_band)), featuring [Alec Bathgate](/Alec_Bathgate). Though short-lived, their performances captivated a generation of aspiring musicians, including a young [Shayne Carter](/Shayne_Carter), who would go on to form [Bored Games](/Bored_Games), [the DoubleHappys](/The_DoubleHappys), and [Straitjacket Fits](/Straitjacket_Fits). Knox himself later founded [Tall Dwarfs](/Tall_Dwarfs), a crucial influence on the emergence of home-recorded [lo-fi indie](/Lo-fi_music) [56].

The nascent [Dunedin](/Dunedin) scene was also imbued with a subtle, yet potent, political undercurrent, often expressing opposition to the government of [Robert Muldoon](/Robert_Muldoon) through satire or outright critique [57]. Musically, these bands took the raw energy of [punk rock](/Punk_rock) but, crucially, stripped away its overt aggression, layering it instead with copious [reverb](/Reverb) and a distinctly [pop](/Pop_music)-influenced sensibility. The sound was characterized by the jangly, often droning guitars and indistinct vocals that marked [the Clean](/The_Clean)'s 1981 debut single "Tally-Ho!" and the influential 1982 *[Dunedin Double](/Dunedin_Double_(EP))* EP, which showcased [the Chills](/The_Chills), [Sneaky Feelings](/Sneaky_Feelings), [the Verlaines](/The_Verlaines), and [the Stones](/The_Stones_(band)) [58]. This unique sonic aesthetic soon radiated outwards, influencing other New Zealand cities like [Christchurch](/Christchurch) and [Auckland](/Auckland) [59] [55] [60] [54]. A small, isolated nation, proving that genuine creativity can bloom anywhere, regardless of geographic convenience.

## History

### Origins

[British band](/British_rock_music) [the Jesus and Mary Chain](/The_Jesus_and_Mary_Chain) performing in California in 2007

The early to mid-1980s witnessed the rather accidental rise of [college radio](/Campus_radio) stations, particularly across the [United States](/United_States). These stations, with their less constrained playlists, became unexpected havens for independent artists from a diverse array of genres, including [alternative rock](/Alternative_rock), [new wave](/New_wave_music), [post-hardcore](/Post-hardcore), and [post-punk](/Post-punk). The bands that found airtime on these eclectic stations were collectively, and rather uncreatively, dubbed "[college rock](/College_rock)" by their listeners – a term that, much like "indie," offered no real stylistic insight. The undisputed titans of this early "college rock" era were the [jangle pop](/Jangle_pop) groups [R.E.M.](/R.E.M.) from the US and [the Smiths](/The_Smiths) from the UK. [Matthew Bannister](/Matthew_Bannister_(musician)), with a certain weariness, identifies these as the earliest true indie rock groups [61]. Their influence was immediate and widespread, quickly inspiring the formation of bands like [Let's Active](/Let%27s_Active), [the Housemartins](/The_Housemartins), and [the La's](/The_La%27s) [62].

It was during this period that "indie rock" began its semantic shift, moving from a descriptor of a band's record label to a nascent musical style itself. This made it, rather uniquely, the only genre of its time defined primarily by its distribution method rather than its inherent sound [9]. Journalist Steve Taylor also noted the bands of the [Paisley Underground](/Paisley_Underground) scene as early indie groups [63]. In subsequent years, the sonic landscape evolved further, as [the Jesus and Mary Chain](/The_Jesus_and_Mary_Chain) and the bands from [Flying Nun Records](/Flying_Nun_Records), such as the [Jean-Paul Sartre Experience](/Jean-Paul_Sartre_Experience), began to steer the genre towards a slower, darker, and more hypnotic aesthetic [61]. The decline of [college radio](/Campus_radio) stations in the US, largely due to [NPR](/NPR)'s lobbying efforts in the 1980s, eventually led to the term "college rock" falling out of favor, replaced, with a sigh of inevitability, by "indie" [64].

### Development

[My Bloody Valentine](/My_Bloody_Valentine_(band)) pioneered the indie rock subgenre [shoegaze](/Shoegaze).

Across the Atlantic, the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) was busy cementing its own indie identity. In 1986, [NME](/NME) released the now-legendary [C86](/C86) compilation cassette. This collection, featuring tracks from groups like [Primal Scream](/Primal_Scream), [the Pastels](/The_Pastels), and [the Wedding Present](/The_Wedding_Present), was ostensibly a snapshot of the contemporary UK independent music scene. It presented a blend of [jangle pop](/Jangle_pop), [post-punk](/Post-punk), and a [Phil Spector](/Phil_Spector)-esque [Wall of Sound](/Wall_of_Sound) [65]. [Bob Stanley](/Bob_Stanley_(musician)), in 2006, rather dramatically, called it "the beginning of indie music" [65]. [C86](/C86) quickly transcended its role as a compilation, becoming a genre descriptor in its own right, applied to bands on the tape and those it influenced, often alongside terms like "anorak pop" and "shambling" [66]. While some [C86](/C86) bands, like [the Soup Dragons](/The_Soup_Dragons) (who sold out [Madison Square Garden](/Madison_Square_Garden)) and [Primal Scream](/Primal_Scream) (recipients of the inaugural [Mercury Prize](/Mercury_Prize)), achieved significant commercial and critical acclaim, many others, as is often the case, faded into obscurity [67]. A familiar tale of fleeting fame.

In the [United States](/United_States), the mainstream success of [R.E.M.](/R.E.M.) inadvertently created a space within the [underground music](/Underground_music) scene for those who recoiled from the aggression and rigid ideology of [hardcore punk](/Hardcore_punk). This opened the floodgates for a diverse array of musicians, particularly within the burgeoning [post-hardcore](/Post-hardcore) scene, epitomized by [the Minutemen](/Minutemen_(band)) [68]. These bands often faced hostility from hardcore purists; [Pitchfork](/Pitchfork_(website)) [69] recounts that "the first time they opened for [Black Flag](/Black_Flag_(band)), the Minutemen were showered with spit from the crowd," noting, rather plainly, that "they just weren't that hardcore" [69]. Despite this, they are credited with providing "the life blood of indie rock for decades" [68] [70] [71]. Similarly, [Wipers](/Wipers_(band)), with their melodic riffs and emphasis on intricate guitar leads and solos, stood out in the hardcore landscape, influencing emerging indie artists like [J Mascis](/J_Mascis) of [Dinosaur Jr](/Dinosaur_Jr.) and helping to reintroduce guitar virtuosity to alternative music [72] [73]. A subtle rebellion within a rebellion, perhaps.

Predictably, major labels, ever on the hunt for the next big thing, began to court these underground bands. Both [Hüsker Dü](/H%C3%BCsker_D%C3%BC) and [the Replacements](/The_Replacements_(band)) released albums on majors in the mid-decade. While these ventures didn't replicate the runaway success of [R.E.M.](/R.E.M.), and the major labels soon lost interest, they left a significant impact on younger bands. Groups such as [Camper Van Beethoven](/Camper_Van_Beethoven) [74], [the Dead Milkmen](/The_Dead_Milkmen) [75], and [Violent Femmes](/Violent_Femmes) [76] injected the scene with a much-needed dose of sardonic humor and irony. As the 1980s drew to a close, [Sonic Youth](/Sonic_Youth), [Dinosaur Jr.](/Dinosaur_Jr.), and [Unrest](/Unrest_(band)) began releasing their own music on independent labels, heavily indebted to these earlier acts, and soon found themselves categorized under the ever-expanding "indie rock" umbrella [77]. The cycle of co-option continued, with [Sonic Youth](/Sonic_Youth) and [the Pixies](/The_Pixies) eventually signing to major labels [78].

The late 1980s also saw the emergence of [shoegaze](/Shoegaze), an indie rock subgenre that pushed the [Wall of Sound](/Wall_of_Sound) production pioneered by groups like [the Jesus and Mary Chain](/The_Jesus_and_Mary_Chain) to its extreme. Merging this dense sonic approach with influences from [Dinosaur Jr.](/Dinosaur_Jr.) and the ethereal [Cocteau Twins](/Cocteau_Twins), shoegaze created a dark, droning, and often cacophonous style where instruments often became indistinguishable from one another. [My Bloody Valentine](/My_Bloody_Valentine_(band)), with their early EPs and debut album *[Isn't Anything](/Isn%27t_Anything)*, were the undisputed pioneers of this immersive sound [79]. Their unique style inspired a wave of bands in London and the [Thames Valley](/Thames_Valley) area, including [Chapterhouse](/Chapterhouse_(band)), [Moose](/Moose_(band)), and [Lush](/Lush_(band)). This interconnected scene was famously, and rather self-referentially, dubbed "the Scene That Celebrates Itself" by [Melody Maker](/Melody_Maker)'s [Steve Sutherland](/Steve_Sutherland_(DJ)) in 1990 [80]. Because nothing says "independent" like a collective pat on the back.

[The Stone Roses](/The_Stone_Roses)' 1990 [Spike Island](/Spike_Island_(concert)) concert was the highest attendance performance by an independent artist of its time.

[Madchester](/Madchester) was another distinct style and scene that erupted in the late 1980s, centered, as its name suggests, in [Manchester](/Manchester). This movement was a hedonistic fusion of [C86](/C86) indie rock, [dance music](/Dance_music), and the burgeoning [rave culture](/Rave), particularly its embrace of psychedelic drugs [81] [82]. The scene revolved around [the Haçienda](/The_Ha%C3%A7ienda) nightclub, an ambitious venture launched in May 1982 by [Factory Records](/Factory_Records). Initially, the club primarily featured pop and hosted acts like [New Order](/New_Order_(band)) and [the Smiths](/The_Smiths) [83]. By 1989, [Madchester](/Madchester) was in full swing, propelled by the success of [the Happy Mondays](/The_Happy_Mondays)' second album *[Bummed](/Bummed)* and [the Stone Roses](/The_Stone_Roses)' [self-titled debut](/The_Stone_Roses_(album)), which became the genre's defining work. Subsequent years saw the rise of other high-profile acts such as [the Charlatans](/The_Charlatans_(English_band)), [808 State](/808_State), and the [Inspiral Carpets](/Inspiral_Carpets) [84].

The distinctive blend of indie rock and dance music found in [Madchester](/Madchester) quickly earned its own critical labels: "[indie dance](/Indie_dance)" or, more specifically, "[baggy](/Baggy)" [85]. The scene's most infamous moment was the [Spike Island](/Spike_Island_(concert)) concert on May 27, 1990, headlined by [the Stone Roses](/The_Stone_Roses). Attracting some 28,000 attendees and lasting twelve hours, it was an unprecedented event for an independent act, a truly monumental display of collective euphoria [86].

Meanwhile, in [Stourbridge](/Stourbridge), a different kind of indie scene was brewing, one that fearlessly drew influences from [electronic](/Electronic_music), [punk](/Punk_rock), [folk](/Folk_music), and even [hip-hop music](/Hip-hop_music). This eclectic blend was dubbed "[grebo](/Grebo_(music))" by critics. Fronted by [Pop Will Eat Itself](/Pop_Will_Eat_Itself), [the Wonder Stuff](/The_Wonder_Stuff), and [Ned's Atomic Dustbin](/Ned%27s_Atomic_Dustbin), "grebo" was more a label for the geographic scene than a tightly defined genre. Yet, these bands rapidly garnered attention: [Pop Will Eat Itself](/Pop_Will_Eat_Itself)'s 1989 singles "[Wise Up! Sucker](/Wise_Up!_Sucker)" and "[Can U Dig It?](/Can_U_Dig_It%3F)" both stormed the UK Top 40, and [Stourbridge](/Stourbridge) briefly became an unlikely pilgrimage site for young indie rock fans. The seminal albums from this era, released between 1989 and 1993, include [the Wonder Stuff](/The_Wonder_Stuff)'s *[Hup](/Hup_(album))* and *[Never Loved Elvis](/Never_Loved_Elvis)*; [Ned's Atomic Dustbin](/Ned%27s_Atomic_Dustbin)'s *[God Fodder](/God_Fodder)* and *[Are You Normal?](/Are_You_Normal%3F)*; and [Pop Will Eat Itself](/Pop_Will_Eat_Itself)'s *[This Is the Day...This Is the Hour...This Is This!](/This_Is_the_Day...This_Is_the_Hour...This_Is_This!)* and *[The Looks or the Lifestyle?](/The_Looks_or_the_Lifestyle%3F)*. During this golden period, grebo bands were fixtures, often headliners, at [Reading Festival](/Reading_Festival), sold millions of albums, and graced the covers of magazines like [NME](/NME) and [Melody Maker](/Melody_Maker) [87]. What set grebo apart was not just its broad influences, but its deliberate subversion of the often twee or melancholic moods prevalent in other indie acts, opting instead for a heavier, more aggressive sound and aesthetic. The scene expanded to embrace stylistically similar bands from nearby [Leicester](/Leicester): [the Bomb Party](/The_Bomb_Party), [Gaye Bykers on Acid](/Gaye_Bykers_on_Acid), [Crazyhead](/Crazyhead), [the Hunters Club](/The_Hunters_Club), and [Scum Pups](/Scum_Pups) [88]. It was a glorious, messy, and decidedly un-twee moment.

### Mainstream–underground split: 1990s

The success of grunge allowed [Sonic Youth](/Sonic_Youth) to break through into the mainstream. [89]

The early 1990s brought with it the inevitable, and somewhat destructive, force of the [Seattle](/Seattle) [grunge](/Grunge) scene. Its most prominent acts—[Nirvana](/Nirvana_(band)), [Pearl Jam](/Pearl_Jam), [Soundgarden](/Soundgarden), and [Alice in Chains](/Alice_in_Chains)—catapulted into the mainstream [90]. The colossal success of these bands, particularly [Nirvana](/Nirvana_(band)), shone an unprecedented, often blinding, spotlight on the broader indie rock scene. This initiated a crucial shift, where the "indie rock" descriptor began to be supplanted by the more palatable, and ultimately less meaningful, term "[alternative rock](/Alternative_rock)" [89]. As a result, "alternative" shed its original counter-cultural connotations, becoming a catch-all for a commercially diluted, lighter form of music that was now dominating the charts. Carl Swanson of *[New York](/New_York_(magazine))* magazine astutely observed that even the concept of "selling out" lost its bite, as [grunge](/Grunge) demonstrated that even radical niche movements could be co-opted, cementing the fragmentation of culture [91].

Media academic Roy Shuker, in his book *Popular Music: The Key Concepts*, bluntly states that "[Grunge](/Grunge) represented the mainstreaming of the North American indie rock ethic and style of the 1980s" [92]. He further elaborated that a band's "independent" status became "as much a marketing device as [indie rock and alternative rock were an] identifiable 'sound'" [92]. In the wake of this sudden, intense attention, indie rock fractured. One path led to accessible bands eager to cater to the now-popular alternative radio airwaves; the other saw bands retreat further underground, continuing their experimental pursuits [62]. According to [AllMusic](/AllMusic), it was during this schism that "indie rock" solidified its meaning, specifically referring to the style of music created by these underground artists, while their more commercially successful, indie-influenced counterparts were simply rebranded as "alternative rock" [11]. A convenient way to tidy up the mess, for the industry at least.

In a direct, almost defiant, counterpoint to the explosive growth of [grunge](/Grunge), [slowcore](/Slowcore) quietly emerged in the [United States](/United_States) [93]. Loosely defined, this genre embraced glacial tempos, minimalist instrumentation, and profoundly melancholic lyrics [94]. [Galaxie 500](/Galaxie_500), especially their 1989 album *[On Fire](/On_Fire_(Galaxie_500_album))*, proved to be a foundational influence [95] [96], with [Bandcamp Daily](/Bandcamp) writer Robert Rubsam calling them the "fountainhead for all that would come" [97]. The first wave of slowcore bands included [Red House Painters](/Red_House_Painters), [Codeine](/Codeine_(band)), [Bedhead](/Bedhead_(band)), [Ida](/Ida_(band)), and [Low](/Low_(band)). This quiet revolution was geographically diffuse, with artists often operating in isolation, their only connection being a shared aversion to speed and aggression [97].

Around 1991, a younger subset of [grebo](/Grebo_(music)) bands materialized, earning the rather whimsical label of "fraggle" bands [98]. The dominant sound of this movement was a style of indie rock heavily indebted to [punk](/Punk_rock) and [Nirvana](/Nirvana_(band))'s *[Bleach](/Bleach_(Nirvana_album))*, occasionally augmented by the use of [drum machines](/Drum_machines) [99]. [Gigwise](/Gigwise) writer Steven Kline described the aesthetic with a certain affection: "filthy guitars, filthier hair and t-shirts only a mother would wash." Prominent fraggle acts included [Senseless Things](/Senseless_Things), [Mega City Four](/Mega_City_Four), and [Carter the Unstoppable Sex Machine](/Carter_the_Unstoppable_Sex_Machine) [99]. A brief, grubby moment of glory.

[Pavement](/Pavement_(band)) singer/guitarist [Stephen Malkmus](/Stephen_Malkmus)

[Spin](/Spin_(magazine)) writer Charles Aaron declared [Pavement](/Pavement_(band)) and [Guided by Voices](/Guided_by_Voices) as "the two bands that came to exemplify indie rock in this period, and still define the term in many people's minds" [100]. Both bands embraced a deliberate [lo-fi](/Lo-fi_music) production style, romanticizing their [DIY](/DIY_ethic) ethos. [Pavement](/Pavement_(band))'s 1992 album *[Slanted and Enchanted](/Slanted_and_Enchanted)* became a defining artifact of the [slacker rock](/Slacker_rock) subgenre [101]. *Rolling Stone*, in a rare moment of clarity, hailed it as "the quintessential indie rock album," placing it on their list of [the 500 greatest albums of all time](/Rolling_Stone%27s_500_Greatest_Albums_of_All_Time) [102].

In North Carolina's [Research Triangle](/Research_Triangle), a vibrant indie rock scene flourished, spearheaded by groups affiliated with [Merge Records](/Merge_Records) such as [Superchunk](/Superchunk), [Archers of Loaf](/Archers_of_Loaf), and [Polvo](/Polvo). These bands crafted a sound influenced by [hardcore punk](/Hardcore_punk) and [post-punk](/Post-punk) [103]. Publications like *[Entertainment Weekly](/Entertainment_Weekly)*, ever eager to spot the next trend, even began to proclaim [Chapel Hill](/Chapel_Hill,_North_Carolina) the "next Seattle" [104] [105]. [Superchunk](/Superchunk)'s single "[Slack Motherfucker](/Slack_Motherfucker)" is credited with popularizing the "[slacker](/Slacker)" stereotype and becoming a defining anthem of 90s indie rock [106]. Because who doesn't love a good anthem for apathy?

As [Britpop](/Britpop) surged, many of Britain's earlier, more genuinely indie rock bands found themselves overshadowed and, often, forgotten [107]. Fronted by the likes of [Blur](/Blur_(band)), [Oasis](/Oasis_(band)), [Pulp](/Pulp_(band)), and [Suede](/Suede_(band)) [108], the bands of this movement were shrewdly marketed as "underground artists" to compete with the American [grunge](/Grunge) invasion [109]. While [Britpop](/Britpop) certainly owed a stylistic debt to indie rock and initially emerged as an offshoot, it ultimately shed the genre's earlier anti-establishment politics, pulling it firmly into the mainstream. Bands like [Blur](/Blur_(band)) and [Pulp](/Pulp_(band)) even signed to major labels. Politician and academic [Rupa Huq](/Rupa_Huq), in her essay *Labouring the Point? The Politics of Britain in "New Britain"*, argues that [Britpop](/Britpop) "began as an offshoot of the independent British music scene but arguably ended up killing it, as a convergence took place between indie and mainstream, removing the distinctive 'protest' element of British-based independent music" [15]. Music journalist [John Harris](/John_Harris_(critic)) suggested that [Britpop](/Britpop) truly began with the simultaneous release of [Blur](/Blur_(band))'s "[Popscene](/Popscene)" and [Suede](/Suede_(band))'s debut "[The Drowners](/The_Drowners)" in the spring of 1992, noting that "if Britpop started anywhere, it was the deluge of acclaim that greeted Suede's first records: all of them audacious, successful and very, very British" [110]. [Suede](/Suede_(band)) were indeed the first of this new wave of guitar-oriented bands to be embraced by the UK music media as Britain's answer to [Seattle](/Seattle)'s [grunge](/Grunge) sound, their debut album *[Suede](/Suede_(album))* becoming the fastest-selling debut album in the UK [111]. A calculated cultural phenomenon, if ever there was one.

### Diversification

[Sunny Day Real Estate](/Sunny_Day_Real_Estate)'s debut album, *[Diary](/Diary_(Sunny_Day_Real_Estate_album))* (1994), began a new wave of the [emo](/Emo) genre, by incorporating elements of it into their indie rock sound [112]. [Sunny Day Real Estate](/Sunny_Day_Real_Estate) and other second-wave [emo](/Emo) bands, including [Piebald](/Piebald_(band)), [the Promise Ring](/The_Promise_Ring), and [Cap'n Jazz](/Cap%27n_Jazz), consciously distanced the genre from its abrasive [hardcore](/Hardcore_punk) roots, allowing for the development of a much more defined and accessible scene than its first iteration [113]. This softer, more melodic style of [emo](/Emo) eventually infiltrated mainstream culture in the early 2000s, propelled by the platinum-selling success of [Jimmy Eat World](/Jimmy_Eat_World)'s *[Bleed American](/Bleed_American)* (2001) and [Dashboard Confessional](/Dashboard_Confessional)'s *[The Places You Have Come to Fear the Most](/The_Places_You_Have_Come_to_Fear_the_Most)* (2001) [114]. One particularly notable offshoot during this period was the [Midwest emo](/Midwest_emo) bands of the latter half of the decade, who skillfully incorporated the jangly guitar tones of earlier indie rock and the rhythmic complexities of [math rock](/Math_rock) to forge the distinctive sound of groups like [American Football](/American_Football_(band)) [113]. The rise of [emo](/Emo) also inadvertently brought significant attention to a number of "not-quite-indie-not-quite-emo" bands such as [Death Cab For Cutie](/Death_Cab_For_Cutie), [Modest Mouse](/Modest_Mouse), and [Karate](/Karate_(band)) [115]. Because labels, much like emotions, are rarely clear-cut.

The loosely defined [Elephant 6](/Elephant_6) collective—a vibrant, if somewhat chaotic, constellation of bands including [the Apples in Stereo](/The_Apples_in_Stereo), [Beulah](/Beulah_(band)), [Circulatory System](/Circulatory_System_(band)), [Elf Power](/Elf_Power), [the Minders](/The_Minders), [Neutral Milk Hotel](/Neutral_Milk_Hotel), [of Montreal](/Of_Montreal), and [the Olivia Tremor Control](/The_Olivia_Tremor_Control)—skillfully merged indie rock with a distinctly [psychedelic pop](/Psychedelic_pop) sensibility. Andrew Earles, author of *[Gimme Indie Rock](/Gimme_Indie_Rock:_500_Essential_American_Underground_Rock_Albums_1981%E2%80%931996)*, credits this collective, particularly [Neutral Milk Hotel](/Neutral_Milk_Hotel) with their 1996 album *[On Avery Island](/On_Avery_Island)*, with "help[ing] keep the genre artistically relevant while other bands defected and other underground styles rose to prominence" [116] [117]. A commendable effort to maintain integrity in a constantly shifting landscape.

[Indie electronic](/Indie_electronic) or [indietronica](/Indietronica) [118] describes a fascinating convergence of rock-based artists and electronic music, incorporating samplers, synthesizers, drum machines, and computer programming into their sound [119]. Less a coherent style and more a broad categorization, it emerged in the early 1990s as a logical progression, drawing from the traditions of early electronic pioneers (like the [BBC Radiophonic Workshop](/BBC_Radiophonic_Workshop)), the motorik rhythms of [krautrock](/Krautrock), and the sleek aesthetics of [synth-pop](/Synth-pop) [119]. English bands [Disco Inferno](/Disco_Inferno_(band)), [Stereolab](/Stereolab), and [Space](/Space_(UK_band)) were key progenitors [119]. Most musicians operating in this space found homes on independent labels such as [Warp](/Warp_(record_label)), [Morr Music](/Morr_Music), [Sub Pop](/Sub_Pop), or [Ghostly International](/Ghostly_International) [119]. A sensible evolution, if a little sterile at times.

[Space rock](/Space_rock), meanwhile, took the sprawling [psychedelic rock](/Psychedelic_rock) and [ambient music](/Ambient_music) influences of bands like [Pink Floyd](/Pink_Floyd) and [Hawkwind](/Hawkwind) and recontextualized them within an indie rock framework. This cosmic style began with [Spacemen 3](/Spacemen_3) in the 1980s, expanding to include later groups such as [Spiritualized](/Spiritualized), [Flying Saucer Attack](/Flying_Saucer_Attack), [Godspeed You! Black Emperor](/Godspeed_You!_Black_Emperor), and [Quickspace](/Quickspace) [120]. Because sometimes, you just need to gaze at the stars and let the guitars drone.

As [Britpop](/Britpop) inevitably began to wane towards the close of the decade, [post-Britpop](/Post-Britpop) emerged, subtly reshaping the UK's indie rock scene [121]. From approximately 1997 onwards, a growing disillusionment with the "Cool Britannia" concept and the general dissolution of [Britpop](/Britpop) as a coherent movement led emerging bands to consciously distance themselves from the label, even while their music remained undeniably derived from it [122] [123]. After [Britpop](/Britpop)'s decline, these bands began to garner increased critical and popular attention [122]. [The Verve](/The_Verve)'s *[Urban Hymns](/Urban_Hymns)* (1997) became a global phenomenon and their commercial zenith before their 1999 breakup. [Radiohead](/Radiohead)—who, despite achieving moderate recognition with *[The Bends](/The_Bends_(album))* in 1995—achieved near-universal critical acclaim with their experimental third album *[OK Computer](/OK_Computer)* (1997), and further solidified their status with its follow-ups, *[Kid A](/Kid_A)* (2000) and *[Amnesiac](/Amnesiac_(album))* (2001) [124].

[Stereophonics](/Stereophonics) incorporated elements of [post-grunge](/Post-grunge) and [hardcore](/Hardcore_punk) on their breakthrough albums *[Word Gets Around](/Word_Gets_Around)* (1997) and *[Performance and Cocktails](/Performance_and_Cocktails)* (1999), before gracefully transitioning into more melodic territory with *[Just Enough Education to Perform](/Just_Enough_Education_to_Perform)* (2001) and subsequent releases [125] [126]. [Feeder](/Feeder_(band)), initially more influenced by American [post-grunge](/Post-grunge), developed a hard rock sound that spawned their breakthrough single "[Buck Rogers](/Buck_Rogers_(song))" and the album *[Echo Park](/Echo_Park_(album))*(2001) [127]. Following the tragic death of their drummer [Jon Lee](/Jon_Lee_(drummer)), they shifted to a more reflective and introspective mode on *[Comfort in Sound](/Comfort_in_Sound)* (2002), which became their most commercially successful album to that point, generating a string of hit singles [128]. The most commercially dominant band of the new millennium proved to be [Coldplay](/Coldplay), whose first two albums, *[Parachutes](/Parachutes_(Coldplay_album))* (2000) and *[A Rush of Blood to the Head](/A_Rush_of_Blood_to_the_Head)* (2002), achieved [multi-platinum](/Music_recording_sales_certification) status, establishing them as global titans by the time of their third album *[X&Y](/X%26Y)* (2005) [129] [130]. And, in a testament to the enduring power of a catchy tune, [Snow Patrol](/Snow_Patrol)'s "[Chasing Cars](/Chasing_Cars)" (from their 2006 album *[Eyes Open](/Eyes_Open_(Snow_Patrol_album))*) holds the dubious honor of being the most widely played song of the 21st century on UK radio [131]. Because sometimes, blandness truly triumphs.

## Mainstream success: 2000s

### Post-punk and garage rock revival

[The Strokes](/The_Strokes) are one of the most influential bands to indie rock in the 2000s.

The 2000s marked a peculiar moment when indie rock, against all prior inclinations, re-entered the mainstream consciousness. This resurgence was largely ignited by [the Strokes](/The_Strokes) and their 2001 debut album, *[Is This It](/Is_This_It)*. Playing a style consciously indebted to 60s and 70s legends like [the Velvet Underground](/The_Velvet_Underground) and [the Ramones](/The_Ramones), the band's stated musical ambition was to sound like "a band from the past that took a time trip into the future to make their record" [132]. The album, a refreshing jolt of raw energy, peaked at number thirty-three in the [United States](/United_States), lingering on the charts for two years, and debuted at an impressive number two on the [UK albums chart](/UK_albums_chart) [132] [133]. At a time when "rock music" was largely defined by the dreary sounds of [post-grunge](/Post-grunge), the aggressive banality of [nu metal](/Nu_metal), and the awkward fusion of [rap rock](/Rap_rock), [the Strokes](/The_Strokes)' stripped-down, throwback [garage rock](/Garage_rock) offered a stark, exhilarating contrast. Their immediate, undeniable influence paved the way for other classic rock-inspired New York bands like the [Yeah Yeah Yeahs](/Yeah_Yeah_Yeahs), [Interpol](/Interpol_(band)), and [TV on the Radio](/TV_on_the_Radio) to gain mainstream attention [134].

[The Strokes](/The_Strokes) were not alone in this commercial breakthrough. They were accompanied by [the White Stripes](/The_White_Stripes), [the Vines](/The_Vines_(band)), and [the Hives](/The_Hives). These groups were swiftly, and rather lazily, christened "The" bands by parts of the media, hailed as nothing less than "the saviours of rock 'n' roll" [135]. This prompted *[Rolling Stone](/Rolling_Stone)* magazine to declare, with characteristic hyperbole, on its September 2002 cover, "Rock is Back!" [136]. Because apparently, it had gone somewhere.

[The Libertines](/The_Libertines) were described by [AllMusic](/AllMusic) as "one of the U.K.'s most influential 21st century acts".

[The Strokes](/The_Strokes)' success injected much-needed vitality into the then-stagnant [post-Britpop](/Post-Britpop) scene in the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom). A new wave of British acts, drawing inspiration from [the Strokes](/The_Strokes) while adding their own experimental flourishes, began to emerge. This first wave included [Franz Ferdinand](/Franz_Ferdinand_(band)), [Kasabian](/Kasabian), [Maxïmo Park](/Max%C3%AFmo_Park), [the Cribs](/The_Cribs), [Bloc Party](/Bloc_Party), [Kaiser Chiefs](/Kaiser_Chiefs), and [the Others](/The_Others_(band)) [137]. However, the true British counterpoint to [the Strokes](/The_Strokes) arrived in the form of [the Libertines](/The_Libertines), who had formed in 1997. [AllMusic](/AllMusic) declared them "one of the U.K.'s most influential 21st century acts" [138], while *[The Independent](/The_Independent)* asserted that "the Libertines wanted to be an important band, but they could not have predicted the impact they would have" [139]. Influenced by [the Clash](/The_Clash), [the Kinks](/The_Kinks), [the Smiths](/The_Smiths), and [the Jam](/The_Jam) [138], their distinctive style—tinny, high-register, often acoustic guitar parts layered with lyrics celebrating British [parochial](/Parochialism) pleasures, delivered in authentic English accents—became widely imitated [139]. [The Fratellis](/The_Fratellis), [the Kooks](/The_Kooks), and [the View](/The_View_(band)) were among the acts to achieve significant commercial success in their wake, though the most prominent post-[Libertines](/The_Libertines) band to emerge was [Sheffield](/Sheffield)'s [Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys) [139].

[Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys) were pioneers in leveraging [Internet social networking](/Internet_social_network) for their initial commercial breakthrough [140]. They quickly scored two No. 1 singles, and their 2006 debut album, *[Whatever People Say I Am, That's What I'm Not](/Whatever_People_Say_I_Am,_That%27s_What_I%27m_Not)*, became the fastest-selling debut album in British chart history [141]. A new era, where algorithms could dictate taste, had truly begun.

In this wave of renewed commercial interest, many legacy indie bands, who had toiled in relative obscurity, finally found their way into the mainstream [142]. [Modest Mouse](/Modest_Mouse)'s 2004 album *[Good News for People Who Love Bad News](/Good_News_for_People_Who_Love_Bad_News)* reached the US top 40 and garnered a [Grammy](/Grammy) Award nomination. [Bright Eyes](/Bright_Eyes_(band)), in 2004, saw two singles top the [Billboard](/Billboard_(magazine)) magazine [Hot 100 Single Sales](/Hot_100_Single_Sales) chart [143]. [Death Cab for Cutie](/Death_Cab_For_Cutie)'s 2005 album *[Plans](/Plans_(album))* debuted at number four in the US, remained on the [Billboard](/Billboard_(magazine)) charts for nearly a year, achieved platinum status, and earned a Grammy nomination [144]. This new commercial prominence, coupled with the widespread, often indiscriminate, application of the term "indie" to other forms of popular culture, led numerous commentators to, quite rightly, suggest that "indie rock" had ceased to be a meaningful term at all [145] [146]. The death of a thousand qualifications.

Simultaneously, a second wave of American bands, including [the Black Keys](/The_Black_Keys), [Kings of Leon](/Kings_of_Leon), [the Shins](/The_Shins), [the Bravery](/The_Bravery), [Spoon](/Spoon_(band)), [the Hold Steady](/The_Hold_Steady), and [the National](/The_National_(band)), achieved international recognition [114]. The most commercially dominant band of this particular wave was [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas)'s [the Killers](/The_Killers). Formed in 2001, reportedly after hearing *[Is This It](/Is_This_It)*, they promptly scrapped most of their existing material to rewrite it under [the Strokes](/The_Strokes)' undeniable influence [147]. Their debut single, "[Mr. Brightside](/Mr._Brightside)," has since achieved a truly staggering level of ubiquity, spending 260 non-consecutive weeks (a full five years) on the [UK Singles Chart](/UK_Singles_Chart) as of April 2021, a record for any song [148] [149]. As of 2017, it had charted in 11 of the preceding 13 years [150], including a 35-week run peaking at number 49 in 2016–2017 [151]. It was the UK's most streamed pre-2010 song until late 2018 [152] and continued to be downloaded hundreds of times a week by 2017 [153]. By March 2018, the song had achieved the remarkable milestone of 200 weeks in the Top 100 of the [UK Singles Chart](/UK_Singles_Chart) [153]. A testament not to genius, perhaps, but to sheer, relentless endurance.

### Landfill indie

[Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys) are one of the most commercially successful bands to emerge out of the [landfill indie](/Landfill_indie) movement.

The seismic impact of [the Strokes](/The_Strokes), [the Libertines](/The_Libertines), and [Bloc Party](/Bloc_Party) generated a significant surge of major label interest in indie rock artists, a trend further amplified by the runaway success of the [Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys). In the years following *[Whatever People Say I Am, That's What I'm Not](/Whatever_People_Say_I_Am,_That%27s_What_I%27m_Not)*, a predictable proliferation of bands emerged—acts like [the Rifles](/The_Rifles_(band)), [the Pigeon Detectives](/The_Pigeon_Detectives), and [Milburn](/Milburn_(band))—who offered a more formulaic, diluted derivative of their predecessors [154] [137]. By the decade's end, critics, with a collective sigh of exasperation, began to refer to this wave of acts as "[landfill indie](/Landfill_indie)" [155] [156] [157]. The term, coined by [Andrew Harrison](/Andrew_Harrison_(journalist)) of *[the Word](/The_Word_(UK_magazine))* magazine [158], perfectly encapsulated the sense of overwhelming, indistinguishable mediocrity.

A 2020 *[Vice](/Vice_Media)* article, with admirable precision, singled out [Johnny Borrell](/Johnny_Borrell), vocalist of [Razorlight](/Razorlight), as "the one man who defined, embodied and lived Landfill Indie" [154]. This was attributed to his ability to form a "spectacularly middle-of-the-road" band, despite his close proximity to [the Libertines](/The_Libertines)' "desperate kinetic energy, mythologised love-hate dynamic and vision of a dilapidated Britain animated by romance and narcotics" [154]. It seems even proximity to brilliance cannot prevent the gravitational pull of the bland. In a 2009 article for *[the Guardian](/The_Guardian)*, journalist [Peter Robinson](/Peter_Robinson_(journalist)) declared the [landfill indie](/Landfill_indie) movement officially dead, laying the blame squarely at the feet of [the Wombats](/The_Wombats), [Scouting For Girls](/Scouting_For_Girls), and [Joe Lean & the Jing Jang Jong](/Joe_Lean_%26_the_Jing_Jang_Jong), stating: "If landfill indie had been a game of [Buckaroo](/Buckaroo!), those three sent the whole donkey's arse of radio-friendly mainstream guitar band monotony flying high into the air, legs flailing" [159]. A fitting, if slightly undignified, end.

### Continued success: 2010s–present

Despite the dire predictions and the rise of "landfill," commercial successes continued to trickle, and occasionally gush, forth in the 2010s. [Arcade Fire](/Arcade_Fire)'s *[The Suburbs](/The_Suburbs_(Arcade_Fire_album))* (2010), [the Black Keys](/The_Black_Keys)' *[Turn Blue](/Turn_Blue_(album))* (2014), [Kings of Leon](/Kings_of_Leon)'s *[Walls](/Walls_(Kings_of_Leon_album))* (2016), and [the Killers](/The_Killers)' *[Wonderful Wonderful](/Wonderful_Wonderful_(The_Killers_album))* (2017) all reached number one on the [Billboard](/Billboard_(magazine)) charts in the [United States](/United_States) and the official chart in the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), with [Arcade Fire](/Arcade_Fire)'s album even clinching a [Grammy](/Grammy) for Album of The Year in 2011 [160]. Other indie rock acts, including [Florence and the Machine](/Florence_and_the_Machine), [the Decemberists](/The_Decemberists), and [LCD Soundsystem](/LCD_Soundsystem), managed to secure number one singles in the [United States](/United_States) during the decade. [Vampire Weekend](/Vampire_Weekend), [Florence and the Machine](/Florence_and_the_Machine), [Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys), [Bon Iver](/Bon_Iver), [the Killers](/The_Killers), and [the Postal Service](/The_Postal_Service) all achieved platinum-selling records [161]. [Vampire Weekend](/Vampire_Weekend)'s third studio album, *[Modern Vampires of the City](/Modern_Vampires_of_the_City)* (2013), received the [Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album](/Grammy_Award_for_Best_Alternative_Music_Album) in 2014, with [Consequence](/Consequence_(publication)) writer Tyler Clark noting in 2019 that it was still "an indie rock standard bearer in the wider world of music" [161].

[Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys)' fifth album, *[AM](/AM_(Arctic_Monkeys_album))* (2013), was undoubtedly one of the decade's biggest indie rock albums, charting at number one on the [UK Albums Chart](/UK_Albums_Chart) after selling 157,329 copies, making it the second fastest-selling album of the year [162]. With *[AM](/AM_(Arctic_Monkeys_album))*, [Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys) broke a record, becoming the first independent-label band to debut at number one in the UK with their first five albums [163]. As of June 2019, *[AM](/AM_(Arctic_Monkeys_album))* had spent an astonishing 300 weeks in the top 100 of the [UK Albums Chart](/UK_Albums_Chart) [164]. The album also topped charts in [Australia](/Australia), [Belgium](/Belgium) (Flanders), [Croatia](/Croatia), [Slovenia](/Slovenia), [Denmark](/Denmark), [Ireland](/Ireland), the [Netherlands](/Netherlands), [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), and [Portugal](/Portugal), and reached top ten positions in numerous other countries. In the [United States](/United_States), it sold 42,000 copies in its first week, debuting at number six on the [Billboard 200](/Billboard_200) chart, making it the band's highest-charting album there [165]. By August 2017, *[AM](/AM_(Arctic_Monkeys_album))* was certified [platinum](/RIAA_certification) by the [RIAA](/RIAA) for combined sales and [album-equivalent units](/Album-equivalent_unit) exceeding a million in the [United States](/United_States) [166]. And, in a testament to its pervasive influence, as of April 14, 2023, every single track from the album was certified silver or higher by the [BPI](/British_Phonographic_Industry), with "Mad Sounds" being the last to achieve this distinction [167]. A truly dominant, if somewhat exhausting, reign.

When [the 1975](/The_1975)'s audacious merger of indie rock and mainstream pop began to gain commercial traction in the early 2010s, it sparked immediate controversy. They were awarded "Worst Band" at the 2014 [NME Awards](/NME_Awards), only to receive "Best Live Band" at the same awards show three years later [168]. A predictable arc for anything that dares to challenge expectations. [Alternative Press](/Alternative_Press_(magazine)) writer Yasmine Summan declared that "If you could summarize 2013 and 2014 in one album for indie and alternative fans, it would be the 1975's [self-titled release](/The_1975_(album))" [169]. In *[the Guardian](/The_Guardian)*, Mark Beaumont credited [the 1975](/The_1975) as the band to "usher indie into the mainstream," comparing vocalist [Matty Healy](/Matty_Healy)'s influence on the genre to that of [Libertines](/The_Libertines) vocalist [Pete Doherty](/Pete_Doherty) [170]. [Pitchfork](/Pitchfork_(website)), with a rare nod of approval, listed them as one of the most influential artists in music since 1995 [171].

In the wake of [the 1975](/The_1975)'s success, a number of other [indie pop](/Indie_pop) artists found popularity, a phenomenon that some critics, with a collective groan, dubbed "Healywave." This wave notably included [Pale Waves](/Pale_Waves), [the Aces](/The_Aces_(indie_pop_band)), [Joan](/Joan_(band)), [Fickle Friends](/Fickle_Friends), and [No Rome](/No_Rome) [172]. Of this group, [Pale Waves](/Pale_Waves) achieved particular commercial prominence, with their debut album *[My Mind Makes Noises](/My_Mind_Makes_Noises)* peaking at number eight on the UK albums chart, *[Who Am I?](/Who_Am_I%3F_(Pale_Waves_album))* (2021) at number three, and *[Unwanted](/Unwanted_(album))* (2022) at number four [173]. Around the same time, [Wolf Alice](/Wolf_Alice) emerged as a significant force, their second album *[Visions of a Life](/Visions_of_a_Life)* (2017) winning the [Mercury Prize](/Mercury_Prize) in 2018, and their third album *[Blue Weekend](/Blue_Weekend)* (2021) earning a nomination [174]. Writer Martin Young, in a 2021 article for *[Dork](/Dork_(magazine))*, went so far as to claim: "It's impossible to truly state just how important Wolf Alice are. They are the catalyst for almost all the amazing bands you've read about in Dork over the last 5 years" [175]. A bold claim, but in the ever-shifting sands of indie, perhaps a necessary one.

